### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

forms

### Description

If you do the following: 

```
formGroup.valueChanges.subscribe( (formValues) => {
   console.log({formValues});
});
```

you get a key-value pair of all the formValues. 

However, it's not possible to determine which control actually changed, and what was the old value.
I made it work with this trick, comparing the object of previous and current form values:

``` 
pipe(
    startWith<string, any>(myForm.value),
    pairwise()
).subscribe( ([previousFormValues, currentFormValues]) => {

});
```
Then I wrote a method `compareFormObjects()` and track the changes manually. 
However, this can be very complex and comes with many downsides:

Let me just state some reasons:

- Some fields could have some dependencies to other fields -> Many fields could change at the same time. It's quite complex (and error prone) to track all these changes manually
- a BIG downside: The solution with comparing objects doesn't work with disabled fields. Since `valueChanges` emits only `myForm.value` and not `myForm.getRawValue()`, the state of disabled fields is not tracked and leads to bigger problems.
- Sometimes you have cases like: You want to add an entire `FormControl` to a `FormArray`. Here you would have many changes between the previous values and the current values, and it's very hard to track them.
- Sometimes your value is an object itself (for example a date object). Then, it's even harder to find out what changed, because the method for comparing the form objects might fail (it might think that it's a nested object where it has to go deeper, like for example in a nested form

That's just a few reasons I ran into my now 4 months old project in a corporate environment. There's many more, and most of them come down to the fact that I cannot determine the origin of the change.


I could also put a listener on each control to track it's changed value. However, in my form there are about 50 controls and many of them are dynamic, so that's not an option at all.

### Proposed solution

`valueChanges` could emit an object which holds all the necessary information:

```
formGroup.valueChanges.subscribe( (formValues: FormValueChange) => {
   console.log({formValues});
});

export interface FormValueChange {
    // the actual form values, so the thing which is currently returned (key-value pair of the form values)
    values: any;
    changedControl: {
        // changed formControlName
        name: string;
        oldValue: any;
        newValue: any;
    }
}
```

### Alternatives considered

See my workaround from above.
However, for complex forms it makes the form/app very error prone.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Signals can become much easier to log and debug, if they were to support optional `name` string on the prototype, just like a regular ES6 class does. We then can easily track named signals, log them, and have a much better picture of what is going on, which includes the production mode.


### Proposed solution

* Extend [CreateSignalOptions](https://angular.io/api/core/CreateSignalOptions) with `name` option:

```ts
interface CreateSignalOptions<T> {
  name?: string;
  equal?: ValueEqualityFn<T>
}
```

* Probably: Extend [Signal](https://angular.io/api/core/Signal) with the same property:

```ts
type Signal<T> = (() => T) & {
    name?: string;
    [SIGNAL]: unknown;
};
```

The name is to be available on the prototype:

```ts
const s1 = signal(1);
const s2 = signal(2, {name: 'second'});

console.log(s1.name); //=> undefined
console.log(s2.name); //=> "second"
```

Internally, it should set the name like this:

```ts
this.name = typeof value === 'string' ? value : JSON.stringify(value);
```

so it is `undefined` only when the name is undefined, and a string for everything else, including `null`, which `JSON.stringify` will make sure of automatically. Even better, with this approach one can even set a name as a serialized object, if needed.

### Alternatives considered

None.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

router

### Description

Currently, you can eagerly load an entire route config, but if you include providers, guards, and other tokens they will be included in the main bundle even for a lazy loaded component/routes.

```ts
[
  {
    path: 'page',
    canActivate: [authGuardFunction, permissionsGuardFunction],
    loadChldren: () => import('features/page')
  },
  {
    path: 'other-page',
    canActivate: [authGuardFunction, permissionsGuardFunction],
    loadComponent: () => import('about.component')
  }
]
```

This feature would allow you to provide a route config with a `path` and a `loadConfig/loadRoute` that resolves to the rest of the route configuration, and would be resolved on the matching of that path before proceeding. This would reduce the main bundle size for route-level configuration, while allowing the entire routing tree to be defined eagerly.

### Proposed solution

Allow lazy loading of the entire route config except for the path

```ts
// features/page.ts
const config: RouteConfig =  {
  canActivate: [authGuardFunction, permissionsGuardFunction],
  component: FeatureHome,
  children: [
    // more lazy loaded routes
  ]
}

export default config;
```

```ts
[
  {
    path: 'page',
    loadConfig: () => import('features/page')
    // or
    loadRoute: () => import('features/page')
  }
]
```

### Alternatives considered

In Analog, file-based routing is used along with `loadChildren` to lazy load the entire route config

```ts
[
  {
    path: 'page',
    loadChildren: () => import('features/page').then(m => {
      return [
       {
          path: '',
          component: m.default,
          ...m.routeMeta
       }
      ];
    })
  }
]
```

